Titanic Survival Prediction¶

The sinking of the Titanic is one of the most infamous shipwrecks in history.

On April 15, 1912, during her maiden voyage, the widely considered unsinkable RMS Titanic sank after colliding with an iceberg. Unfortunately, there werent enough lifeboats for everyone onboard, resulting in the death of 1502 out of 2224 passengers and crew.

While there was some element of luck involved in surviving, it seems some groups of people were more likely to survive than others.

In this project, a predictive model is being developed that tries to answer the question: what sorts of people were more likely to survive? using passenger data (ie name, age, gender, socio-economic class, etc).

The data was acquired from Kaggle.

The GitHub repository for this project can be found here.

Data Description¶

Survival: 0 = No, 1 = Yes

Pclass (Ticket class): 1 = 1st, 2 = 2nd, 3 = 3rd

Sex: Gender

Age: Age in years

SibSp: number of siblings/spouses aboard the Titanic

Parch: number of parents/children aboard the Titanic

Ticket: Ticket number

Fare: Passenger fare

Cabin: Cabin number

Embarked: Port of Embarkation, C = Cherbourg, Q = Queenstown, S = Southampton

46.75 that embarked in Queenstown were women

We know that females were more likely to survive. The percentage of women who embarked in Cherbourg and in Queenstown was quite similar, but the survival rate differs.

Queenstown first class tickets: 2
Queenstown second class tickets: 3
Cherbourg  first class tickets: 85

From the above information we understand that the difference in the survival rate is due to the class of tickets.

General Conclusion:¶

Young children, elderly people, women and first class tickets passengers had a higher survival rate. This confirms part of the "Women and children first" policy.

# Plot non-normalized confusion matrix
model = LogisticRegression()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)
titles_options = [("Confusion matrix, without normalization", None),
                  ("Normalized confusion matrix", 'true')]
for title, normalize in titles_options:
    disp = plot_confusion_matrix(model, X_test, y_test,
                                 display_labels='Survived',
                                 cmap=plt.cm.Blues,
                                 normalize=normalize)
    disp.ax_.set_title(title)

    print(title)
    print(disp.confusion_matrix)

plt.show()
